## Business Logic

### 1. Summary of the Account Management Service
The Account Management Service provides a comprehensive solution for managing user accounts. It allows end users to create, retrieve, update, and delete account records while ensuring that each account has a unique identifier. The service incorporates an external validation mechanism to confirm account status before executing specific operations. Notifications are sent through an asynchronous messaging system whenever accounts are created or updated, facilitating real-time updates across systems. The service manages data persistence through a relational database for account information and a non-relational database for bank-related details. The architecture ensures data integrity through proper transformations between data models and data transfer objects, and it includes robust error handling to manage exceptions that may arise during account operations.

### 2. Table of Base Path, Source Repository, and Description

| **Base Path**          | **Source Repository**                     | **Description**                                                              |
|------------------------|-------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `/accounts`            | [GitHub Repo Link](#)                    | API for managing user accounts, including creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion of account records. |

### 3. Overall API Specification

| Endpoint               | Method | Authentication | Description                                   | Request Body                     | Response Code | Response Body                |
|-----------------------|--------|----------------|-----------------------------------------------|----------------------------------|---------------|-------------------------------|
| `/accounts`           | GET    | No             | Retrieve all accounts                         | None                             | 200           | List of Account objects       |
| `/accounts`           | POST   | No             | Create a new account                          | Account object                   | 201           | Created Account object        |
| `/accounts/{id}`      | GET    | No             | Retrieve account by ID                        | None                             | 200           | Account object                |
|                       |        |                |                                               |                                  | 404           | Not Found                     |
| `/accounts/{id}`      | PUT    | No             | Update an existing account                    | Account object                   | 200           | Updated Account object        |
|                       |        |                |                                               |                                  | 404           | Not Found                     |
| `/accounts/{id}`      | DELETE | No             | Delete an account                             | None                             | 204           | No Content                    |
|                       |        |                |                                               |                                  | 404           | Not Found                     |

### 4. Endpoints Summary
- **GET `/accounts`**: Retrieves all accounts.
- **POST `/accounts`**: Creates a new account.
- **GET `/accounts/{id}`**: Retrieves an account by its unique identifier.
- **PUT `/accounts/{id}`**: Updates an existing account by its unique identifier.
- **DELETE `/accounts/{id}`**: Deletes an account by its unique identifier. 

This structured breakdown presents a clear overview of the service, its functionalities, and its API specifications.

## Plant UML script

Here is a PlantUML sequence diagram script based on the provided business logic for the account management system:

```plantuml
@startuml
actor EndUser
participant "Account Service" as AccountService
participant "Account Feign Client" as AccountFeignClient
participant "Database (PostgreSQL)" as PostgreSQL
participant "Database (MongoDB)" as MongoDB
participant "RabbitMQ" as RabbitMQ
participant "Kafka" as Kafka

== Create Account ==
EndUser -> AccountService: POST /accounts\n(AccountDTO)
AccountService -> AccountService: Check if account exists
alt Account exists
    AccountService -> EndUser: 400 Bad Request\n(BadRequestException)
else Account does not exist
    AccountService -> AccountFeignClient: Validate account status
    AccountFeignClient -> AccountService: Status valid
    AccountService -> PostgreSQL: Save AccountEntity
    PostgreSQL -> AccountService: Account saved
    AccountService -> RabbitMQ: Publish account creation message
    RabbitMQ -> AccountService: Message published
    AccountService -> EndUser: 201 Created\n(Created Account)
end

== Get All Accounts ==
EndUser -> AccountService: GET /accounts
AccountService -> PostgreSQL: Retrieve all accounts
PostgreSQL -> AccountService: List of AccountEntities
AccountService -> EndUser: 200 OK\n(List of AccountDTOs)

== Get Account by ID ==
EndUser -> AccountService: GET /accounts/{id}
AccountService -> PostgreSQL: Retrieve AccountEntity by ID
alt Account not found
    AccountService -> EndUser: 404 Not Found\n(ResourceNotFoundException)
else Account found
    AccountService -> EndUser: 200 OK\n(AccountDTO)
end

== Update Account ==
EndUser -> AccountService: PUT /accounts/{id}\n(AccountDTO)
AccountService -> AccountService: Check if account exists
alt Account exists
    AccountService -> AccountFeignClient: Validate account status
    AccountFeignClient -> AccountService: Status valid
    AccountService -> PostgreSQL: Update AccountEntity
    PostgreSQL -> AccountService: Account updated
    AccountService -> Kafka: Publish account update message
    Kafka -> AccountService: Message published
    AccountService -> EndUser: 200 OK\n(Updated Account)
else Account does not exist
    AccountService -> EndUser: 404 Not Found\n(ResourceNotFoundException)
end

== Delete Account ==
EndUser -> AccountService: DELETE /accounts/{id}
AccountService -> AccountService: Check if account exists
alt Account exists
    AccountService -> PostgreSQL: Delete AccountEntity
    PostgreSQL -> AccountService: Account deleted
    AccountService -> EndUser: 204 No Content
else Account does not exist
    AccountService -> EndUser: 404 Not Found\n(ResourceNotFoundException)
end
@enduml
```

### Explanation of the Diagram:
1. **Actors and Participants**: The diagram includes all key actors such as `EndUser`, `Account Service`, `Account Feign Client`, `PostgreSQL`, `MongoDB`, `RabbitMQ`, and `Kafka`.
2. **Main Interactions**: Each key business process (Create, Retrieve, Update, Delete) is represented with clear interactions between the participants.
3. **Decision Points**: The diagram highlights critical decision points, such as checking if an account exists and validating account status before proceeding with operations.
4. **Descriptive Messages**: Each message between actors is descriptive, indicating the action being taken, the endpoint being called, and the status returned.
5. **Components Involved**: All components mentioned in the business logic, including the databases and messaging systems, are included.
6. **Publishing Messages**: The diagram specifies which messaging system (RabbitMQ or Kafka) is used for publishing messages during account creation and updates.

This sequence diagram provides a comprehensive view of the interactions and processes in the account management system as per the provided business logic.

# API Documentation

## /accounts GET
Endpoint URL: /accounts  
HTTP Method: GET  
Authentication: Bearer Token Required  
Authorization: None  
Description: Retrieve all accounts.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                          |
|----------------|--------|----------|--------------------------------------|
| None           | N/A    | No       | No request body is required for this endpoint. |

### Sample Request
```json
{}
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name     | Type   | Description                          |
|----------------|--------|--------------------------------------|
| accounts       | Array  | List of Account objects              |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "accounts": [
    {
      "id": "1",
      "name": "John Doe",
      "email": "john.doe@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "1234567890",
      "accountType": "savings",
      "dob": "1990-01-01",
      "bankCode": "XYZ123"
    }
  ]
}
```

### Components Involved
- Account Service
- PostgreSQL Database

### Data Mapping
| Source Field      | Target Field               | Transformation                |
|-------------------|---------------------------|-------------------------------|
| None              | accounts                  | Direct retrieval from DB      |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "Unauthorized",
  "code": 401,
  "message": "Authentication token is missing or invalid."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name                | Description                                  | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                   |
|---------------------|----------------------------------------------|----------------|--------|---------------------|-------------------------|
| UnauthorizedException| Thrown when the user is not authenticated   | Header         | string | Mandatory            | Token must be provided  |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message      | Description                               |
|-----------|--------------|-------------------------------------------|
| 401       | Unauthorized | Authentication token is missing or invalid.|
| 500       | Internal Server Error | An unexpected error occurred.         |


## /accounts POST
Endpoint URL: /accounts  
HTTP Method: POST  
Authentication: Bearer Token Required  
Authorization: None  
Description: Create a new account.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                          |
|----------------|--------|----------|--------------------------------------|
| account        | Object | Yes      | Account object containing account details. |

### Sample Request
```json
{
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "1234567890",
  "accountType": "savings",
  "dob": "1990-01-01",
  "bankCode": "XYZ123"
}
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name     | Type   | Description                          |
|----------------|--------|--------------------------------------|
| id             | string | Unique identifier for the created account |
| name           | string | Name of the account holder           |
| email          | string | Email of the account holder          |
| accountNumber  | string | Account number                       |
| accountType    | string | Type of account                      |
| dob            | string | Date of birth                        |
| bankCode       | string | Bank code associated with the account|

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "id": "1",
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "1234567890",
  "accountType": "savings",
  "dob": "1990-01-01",
  "bankCode": "XYZ123"
}
```

### Components Involved
- Account Service
- PostgreSQL Database
- RabbitMQ

### Data Mapping
| Source Field      | Target Field               | Transformation                |
|-------------------|---------------------------|-------------------------------|
| account.name      | AccountEntity.name        | Direct mapping                |
| account.email     | AccountEntity.email       | Direct mapping                |
| account.accountNumber | AccountEntity.accountNumber | Direct mapping            |
| account.accountType| AccountEntity.accountType | Direct mapping                |
| account.dob       | AccountEntity.dob         | Direct mapping                |
| account.bankCode  | AccountEntity.bankCode    | Direct mapping                |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "Bad Request",
  "code": 400,
  "message": "Account with this ID already exists."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name                | Description                                  | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                   |
|---------------------|----------------------------------------------|----------------|--------|---------------------|-------------------------|
| BadRequestException  | Thrown when an account with the same ID exists | Payload       | string | Mandatory            | Must be unique          |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message         | Description                               |
|-----------|-----------------|-------------------------------------------|
| 400       | Bad Request     | Account with this ID already exists.      |
| 500       | Internal Server Error | An unexpected error occurred.         |
